## When to use
Use this skill when you need a quick and easy way to monitor your network interface statuses without typing long commands every time.

## Approach
Create a new shell function in your `.bashrc` or equivalent configuration file. Use `shell_exec` to execute the command that retrieves the status of all network interfaces, which can be done with `ip addr show`.

## Example
To create and use this custom shell function:
1. Edit your `.bashrc` file using a KDEV tool like `file_write`.
2. Add the following line at the end of your `.bashrc`: 
   ```shell
   nis() { shell_exec "ip addr show"; }
   ```
3. Source your `.bashrc` to apply changes: `source ~/.bashrc`.
4. Now, you can simply type `nis` in any terminal window to check network interface statuses.

## Pitfalls
- Ensure that the function name (`nis`) does not conflict with existing commands or functions.
- The function may take a moment to execute if there are many interfaces or large IP configurations.